BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Continental Bank Stock Sale: The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. plans to sell 
up to 9 million shares of Continental Bank Corp. common stock in another step 
to return the Chicago-based bank to public ownership, according to Securities 
and Exchange Commission documents. The sale, which would raise about $230 
million, would reduce the FDIC's direct and indirect control of the bank to 
about 26%. Shares of the bank company were up 12.5 cents at $25.50. The FDIC 
put up $4.5 billion in 1984 to rescue the bank, then known as Continental 
Illinois, which was threatened by a run on deposits. After the sale of the 
remainder of the stock, probably later this year, the FDIC's losses are 
expected to total about $2 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
