250,000 HAIR DRYERS TO BE RECALLED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Consumer Product Safety Commission announced today that four companies have 
agreed to recall approximately 250,000 hair dryers that the commission believes 
present a danger of electrocution. 
</P>
<P>
In announcing the voluntary recall, the commission said it estimates that 17 
Americans die each year of accidental electrocution by hair dryers, usually 
when they are dropped into bathtubs. 
</P>
<P>
The firms and the hair dryers involved in the recall are MBR Industries Inc. of 
Miami, maker of Pomair Pro 2100 and 1900; Mustang Electronics Inc. of 
Hallandale, Fla., maker of Mustang MU 2100; Major International Inc. of Orange, 
maker of Major Styling Dryer Model 1250, and China Bazaar of San Francisco, 
Minimate Hair Dryer and Iron DS-601. 
