S. KOREA TO MELT DOWN $13 MILLION WORTH OF UNSOLD '88 OLYMPIC COINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SEOUL 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
South Korea plans to melt down $13 million worth of unsold coins commemorating 
the 1988 Summer Olympics in Seoul, a newspaper reported today. 
</P>
<P>
The Kyonghyang Daily News, a Seoul newspaper, said the Bank of Korea was 
arranging with a Korean firm to melt down about 2.5 million unsold Olympic 
coins whose value was estimated at $13 million. The newspaper accused Olympic 
organizers and bank officials of poor promotion and a half-hearted attitude in 
selling the coins. 
</P>
<P>
Olympic coins were first issued in February, 1987, and the central bank had to 
re-issue the coins four times last year to meet a growing demand. But the 
demand fell off sharply in the months after last year's summer games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
